Exploratory analysis of Star_classification data¶

Analysis to understand better the data obtained and its characteristics. Some models will also be trained to see which one understands and classifies the data better.

Data obtained from: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/fedesoriano/stellar-classification-dataset-sdss17

The definition of the variables can be found in the link provided but here it is a summary of the most important ones:

  • obj_ID = Object Identifier,
  • alpha = Right Ascension angle (at J2000 epoch)
  • delta = Declination angle (at J2000 epoch)
  • u = Ultraviolet filter in the photometric system
  • g = Green filter in the photometric system
  • r = Red filter in the photometric system
  • i = Near Infrared filter in the photometric system
  • z = Infrared filter in the photometric system
  • class = object class (galaxy, star or quasar object)
  • redshift = redshift value based on the increase in wavelength

In [6]:
not_var=['obj_ID','field_ID','class','cam_col','run_ID','rerun_ID','spec_obj_ID','plate','MJD','fiber_ID']

The data doesn't seem to have many null values. They are represented by a -9999 and they seem to be only in the columns corresponding to the observational filters: u, g, r, i, z.
This values will be replaced with the average of their corresponding columns

We are going to plot the variable distributions to check if there are outliers that need to be removed. The plots have the three different classes to see if there are differences between them

In [11]:
for cc in df_train.columns:

    if cc not in not_var:

        for gg in ['GALAXY','STAR','QSO']:

            plt.hist(df_train[df_train['class']==gg][cc],label=gg,edgecolor='black',alpha=0.6)
        plt.legend()
        plt.title(cc)
        plt.show()

After looking at these graphs we can say that:

  • Galaxies are the most common object in the data set
  • All the objects belong to the north hemisphere, delta (declination) has mainly positive values
  • The emision of the objects for the diffeerent filters (u, g, r, i, z) depends on the energy of the object and they present different distributions.
  • Galaxies, Stars and QSO present really different characteristics in the redshift. The visible stars are really close by, they have small redshifts, meanwhile the QSO can be really far away presenting much bigger values.

The data set is not balanced, there are many more galaxies than stars or QSO so we need to balance the dataset before training any model on them.

Balance the data set¶

As we have many examples we are going to undersampling the data instead of trying to generate new registers

no_sample = 5
df_balance=df_train.groupby("class").apply(lambda x: x.sample(minimum_size,replace=True)).reset_index(drop=True)

Logistic Regression¶

Let's start applying the simplest and most direct approach. Data needs to be scalated to obtain good results

In [18]:
scaler = preprocessing.StandardScaler()
x_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(x_train)
x_test_scaled = scaler.transform(x_test)
In [19]:
model = LogisticRegression(solver='saga',max_iter=500)  

model.fit(x_train_scaled, y_train)
y_pred_lr = model.predict(x_test_scaled)
y_proba_lr = model.predict_proba(x_test_scaled)
In [20]:

Support Vector Machines¶

There are two possible options when training a SVM: considering one-vs-rest or one-vs-one. Let's try both of them over the scaled data:

One versus One

In [21]:
model_svc = SVC(kernel='rbf', decision_function_shape='ovo',probability=True) 
model_svc.fit(x_train_scaled, y_train)

y_pred_SVM = model_svc.predict(x_test_scaled)
y_proba_SVM = model_svc.predict_proba(x_test_scaled)

Random Forest¶

Finally, I will try to fit the data with a random forest. Instead of trying just the default model, I will perform a little hyperparameter tunning. As the number of variables is small, I will do it directly with a grid search. In case of having more complex data I would use the H2O autoML function.

In [23]:
estimators=[5,50,100]
depth=[5,10,15]
min_leaf=[1,10,100] 

for est in estimators:
    for dd in depth:
        for min_l in min_leaf:
            
            clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = est ,max_depth=dd,min_samples_leaf=min_l,random_state=0) 

            clf.fit(x_train, y_train)
            y_pred = clf.predict(x_test) 
            y_proba = clf.predict_proba(x_test)
            
            fpr, tpr, thresholds = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=1)
            
            matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
            accur=metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
            
            auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba, multi_class='ovr', average='macro')

            print('trees:{} max_depth:{} min_leaf: {} auc:{}, accuracy:{}'.format(est,dd,min_l,auc,accur) )

Modifying the classification thresholds¶

To try to improve the identification of the quasars let's calculate the f1 score, which balances the precission and the recall of the classification. The thersholds of the probability that provide the best f1 results willl be used in the model

In [33]:
y_true_bin = label_binarize(y_test, classes=[0, 1, 2])  

precision_micro, recall_micro, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true_bin.ravel(), y_proba.ravel())
ap_micro = average_precision_score(y_true_bin, y_proba, average='micro')
In [34]:
best_thresholds = []
for i in range(y_proba.shape[1]):  
    precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_true_bin[:, i], y_proba[:, i])
    f1 = 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall + 1e-8)  
    best_idx = f1.argmax()
    best_thresholds.append((thresholds[best_idx], f1[best_idx]))

def apply_custom_thresholds(y_proba, thresholds):
    predictions = []
    for probs in y_proba:
        above_thresh = [i for i, p in enumerate(probs) if p >= thresholds[i]]
        if len(above_thresh) == 1:
            predictions.append(above_thresh[0])
        elif len(above_thresh) > 1:
            # Pick the one with highest probability
            predictions.append(above_thresh[np.argmax([probs[i] for i in above_thresh])])
        else:
            predictions.append(np.argmax(probs))
    return np.array(predictions)

y_pred_custom = apply_custom_thresholds(y_proba, custom_thresholds)

But, considering that the quasars are a more rare object and their number is smaller in the data we will prioritaze its correct detection. Therefore, we will consider the original thersholds and we will use them to implement the model

Conclussions¶

The study of the data has shown that the redshift is the variable with the biggest impact on the data and that the Random Forest is the best algorithm to classify the data. The results can also be modify changing the decission thersholds but that would depend on the scintific goals and which objects are more valuable for the investigators

I will develop a script to launch in python in which the user would be able to choose between the two best performance models (Random Forest or SVM). The program will allow also to save the model, and to run in two modes: production or evaluation, depending on the goal: to generate prediction for new data or to evaluate the models performance
